1. Introduction & Motivation

The Martian environment imposes constraints requiring a radical rethinking of Environmental Control and Life Support Systems (ECLSS):

Constraints:

1. Mass: ΔV ≈ 4.1 km/s from LMO to surface → ~1,000 kg penalty for excess consumables
2. Latency: 8-22 minute communication delay → autonomous control required
3. Environment: T = -80°C to 20°C daily cycle, 0.6 kPa atmospheric pressure, abrasive dust

Current Technology Limitations:
ISS Sabatier reactor: CO₂ + 4H₂ → CH₄ + 2H₂O (ΔH = -165 kJ/mol)

· Oxygen recovery: ~54%
· Catalyst degradation: Ni/Al₂O₃ deactivates at 2-3% CO concentration
· Requires continuous H₂ import from Earth

CHRSy-AI Innovation:
We propose a catalyst-free Reverse Water-Gas Shift (RWGS) system:

\text{CO}_2 + \text{H}_2 \leftrightarrow \text{CO} + \text{H}_2\text{O} \quad (\Delta H = +41.2\ \text{kJ/mol})

Operating at 850-950°C without catalytic surfaces, integrated with a tri-tiered AI architecture for autonomous optimization.

---

2. Mathematical Foundations of the Catalyst-Free RWGS Process

2.1 Thermodynamic Equilibrium Analysis

The equilibrium constant for the RWGS reaction:

K_p(T) = \frac{P_{\text{CO}} \cdot P_{\text{H}_2\text{O}}}{P_{\text{CO}_2} \cdot P_{\text{H}_2}}

Temperature dependence via van't Hoff equation:

\frac{d\ln K_p}{dT} = \frac{\Delta H^\circ}{RT^2}

Integrating with ΔH ≈ constant:

\ln K_p(T) = \ln K_{p,0} - \frac{\Delta H^\circ}{R}\left(\frac{1}{T} - \frac{1}{T_0}\right)

Where for RWGS:

· ΔH° = 41.2 kJ/mol
· Kₚ(298K) = 8.6×10⁻⁶
· Kₚ(1000K) = 1.06

Extent of Reaction:
Let ε be the reaction extent, with initial moles nᵢ⁰:

\begin{aligned}
n_{\text{CO}_2} &= n_{\text{CO}_2}^0 - \varepsilon \\
n_{\text{H}_2} &= n_{\text{H}_2}^0 - \varepsilon \\
n_{\text{CO}} &= \varepsilon \\
n_{\text{H}_2\text{O}} &= \varepsilon \\
n_{\text{total}} &= n_{\text{total}}^0
\end{aligned}

At equilibrium:

K_p(T) = \frac{\varepsilon^2}{(n_{\text{CO}_2}^0 - \varepsilon)(n_{\text{H}_2}^0 - \varepsilon)} \cdot \left(\frac{P}{n_{\text{total}}^0}\right)^0

Solving for ε:

\varepsilon = \frac{(n_{\text{CO}_2}^0 + n_{\text{H}_2}^0)K_p - \sqrt{(n_{\text{CO}_2}^0 + n_{\text{H}_2}^0)^2K_p^2 - 4(K_p-1)K_p n_{\text{CO}_2}^0 n_{\text{H}_2}^0}}{2(K_p-1)}

2.2 Reaction Kinetics & Carbon Formation Boundaries

RWGS Rate Equation (Homogeneous Gas Phase):

r_{\text{RWGS}} = k_f(T) P_{\text{CO}_2} P_{\text{H}_2} - k_r(T) P_{\text{CO}} P_{\text{H}_2\text{O}}

Arrhenius form:

k_f(T) = A_f \exp\left(-\frac{E_{a,f}}{RT}\right)

k_r(T) = A_r \exp\left(-\frac{E_{a,r}}{RT}\right)

From literature [1]:

· A_f = 10⁸·⁵ mol/(m³·s·Pa²)
· E_{a,f} = 120 kJ/mol
· A_r = 10¹⁰ mol/(m³·s·Pa²)
· E_{a,r} = 160 kJ/mol

Carbon Formation (Boudouard Reaction):

2\text{CO} \leftrightarrow \text{C}(s) + \text{CO}_2 \quad (\Delta H = -172.5\ \text{kJ/mol})

Equilibrium constant:

K_{p,\text{Boud}} = \frac{P_{\text{CO}_2}}{P_{\text{CO}}^2}

Carbon formation occurs when:

\frac{P_{\text{CO}_2}}{P_{\text{CO}}^2} < K_{p,\text{Boud}}(T)

Safe Operating Envelope:
We define the carbon avoidance criterion:

\frac{P_{\text{H}_2}}{P_{\text{CO}_2}} > \alpha(T) = \sqrt{\frac{K_{p,\text{RWGS}}(T)}{K_{p,\text{Boud}}(T)}}

At 950°C (1223K):

· K_{p,\text{RWGS}} ≈ 0.89
· K_{p,\text{Boud}} ≈ 0.032
· α(1223K) ≈ 5.3

Thus, maintaining H₂:CO₂ ratio > 5.3:1 prevents carbon formation thermodynamically.

2.3 Heat Transfer & Energy Balance

Reactor Energy Balance:

\frac{dE}{dt} = \dot{Q}_{\text{in}} - \dot{Q}_{\text{out}} + \dot{W} + \sum \dot{n}_i h_i

For steady-state operation:

0 = \dot{Q}_{\text{heater}} - \dot{Q}_{\text{loss}} + \Delta H_{\text{rxn}} \cdot r_{\text{RWGS}} \cdot V

Heat loss through composite wall:

\dot{Q}_{\text{loss}} = \frac{T_{\text{in}} - T_{\text{amb}}}{\frac{1}{h_i A_i} + \sum \frac{\ln(r_{j+1}/r_j)}{2\pi L k_j} + \frac{1}{h_o A_o}}

Where:

· h_i, h_o = internal/external heat transfer coefficients
· k_j = thermal conductivity of layer j
· T_amb = Martian ambient temperature (variable)

Transient Thermal Response:

\rho C_p \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = k \nabla^2 T + \dot{q}_{\text{gen}}

With Martian diurnal cycle:

T_{\text{amb}}(t) = T_{\text{avg}} + \Delta T \sin\left(\frac{2\pi t}{\tau_{\text{Mars}}} + \phi\right)

τ_Mars = 24h 37m, ΔT ≈ 50°C, T_avg ≈ -30°C

2.4 Mass Conservation Equations

Component Balance in Reactor:

\frac{dn_i}{dt} = F_{\text{in}}y_{i,\text{in}} - F_{\text{out}}y_{i,\text{out}} + R_i V

Where R_i = reaction rate of component i.

Overall System Mass Balance (4 crew):
Oxygen consumption: 0.84 kg/crew/day × 4 = 3.36 kg/day
CO₂ production: 1.00 kg/crew/day × 4 = 4.00 kg/day
H₂O recovery target: 3.02 kg/day (95% of input H₂O)

Hydrogen Parity Condition:
Let H₂_loss be system hydrogen leakage, H₂_metabolic be hydrogen from food:

\text{Parity achieved when: } H_{2,\text{recovered}} + H_{2,\text{metabolic}} \geq H_{2,\text{loss}} + H_{2,\text{process}}

Where:

· H₂_metabolic ≈ 0.07 × 2.4 kg_food/day × 4 crew = 0.67 kg/day
· H₂_loss (target) < 0.01 kg/day
· H₂_process (RWGS consumption) = 0.125 kg/day

Thus need: H₂_recovered ≥ 0.125 + 0.01 - 0.67 = -0.535 kg/day (net gain from food)

