Appendices: CHRSy-AI Conceptual Design & Feasibility Study

Appendix A: Preliminary Risk Catalog & pFMEA Methodology

This appendix details the structured approach for identifying and analyzing risks inherent to the novel CHRSy-AI architecture. The process adheres to SAE International guidelines (ARP4761) adapted for conceptual space systems.

A.1 Risk Identification Framework
Risks will be cataloged through a top-down Functional Hazard Assessment (FHA) and a bottom-up subsystem analysis.

· Functional Hazards: Derived from top-level system requirements (e.g., "Loss of Oxygen Production," "Uncontrolled Hydrogen Release," "False Autonomous Shutdown").
· Subsystem Analysis: Each proposed subsystem (Reactor, AI Controller, CCC, H2 Management) will be examined for potential failure modes based on its operational theory and analogous technologies.

A.2 Preliminary Failure Modes & Effects Analysis (pFMEA) Template
The following table outlines the planned analytical structure. Specific failure modes, effects, and controls will be populated during the study based on modeling outputs.

Item / Function Potential Failure Mode (To Be Analyzed) Postulated Effect on Mission Sev. (Est.) Proposed Mitigation Strategy Analysis
CHRSy Reactor Core Carbon Fouling (Soot) Reduced heat transfer & flow, declining O2 yield, potential clog. 7 Modeling Task: Determine the H2:CO2 ratio "safe window" via ASPEN kinetics modeling to suppress Boudouard reaction.
 Liner Crack (Thermal Fatigue) Loss of pressure containment, process gas leak into habitat. 9 Analysis Task: Perform Low-Cycle Fatigue (LCF) simulation in COMSOL to predict crack initiation cycles for candidate materials.
AI Tier 2 Optimizer Control Instability (Oscillation) Cycling pressure/temperature damages hardware, wastes resources. 8 Simulation Task: Implement and test robust control algorithms (e.g., Proportional-Integral-Derivative with adaptive gain) in the Digital Twin under noise.
 Overfitting to Training Data Poor performance when encountering un-modeled Martian conditions (e.g., novel dust storm). 6 Methodology: Employ k-fold cross-validation during AI training and inject randomized noise/perturbations into synthetic data set.
Cryogenic CO2 Concentrator Water Ice Clogging Blocked cold plates, catastrophic drop in CO2 feed rate. 8 Design Analysis: Model the required pre-cooling and heating cycle timing to manage H2O freeze-out before CO2 deposition.
H2 Storage (Metal Hydride) Contamination-Induced Capacity Loss Reduced H2 buffer, endangering Hydrogen Parity. 7 Modeling Task: Analyze literature on poisoning thresholds for candidate hydrides by trace gases (e.g., CO, O2) to specify purity requirements.

A.3 Risk Assessment & Down-Selection
A Risk Matrix (Likelihood vs. Severity per NASA standards) will be created from the pFMEA. High-scoring risks will become Key Technical Risks and drive priority for deeper analysis in Phase 1 and specific testing in Phase 2.

---

Appendix B: Detailed Modeling & Simulation Plan

This appendix specifies the parameters, tools, and validation steps for the computational work.

B.1 Thermodynamic & Kinetic Model (ASPEN Plus)

· Objective: Verify theoretical feasibility and define the optimal operating envelope.
· Key Reactions Modeled:
  1. Primary RWGS: CO2 + H2 ↔ CO + H2O
  2. Competing Boudouard: 2CO ↔ C(s) + CO2
  3. Methanation: CO + 3H2 ↔ CH4 + H2O
· Parameters Swept: Temperature (800-1000°C), Pressure (1-5 atm), H2:CO2 Inlet Ratio (1:1 to 4:1).
· Success Criteria: Identify a combination where RWGS equilibrium conversion >95% and carbon formation is thermodynamically suppressed.

B.2 CFD & Thermal-Structural Model (ANSYS/COMSOL)

· Objective: Design reactor geometry and assess material survivability.
· Geometry: A 2D axisymmetric model of the packed-bed reactor with insulated housing.
· Boundary Conditions:
  · Internal: Convective heat flux from 950°C gas stream.
  · External: Martian ambient temperature cycle: -80°C to 20°C (diurnal simulation).
  · Material Properties: To be input for Molybdenum TZM alloy and Tungsten alloy as baseline candidates.
· Analysis Outputs: Temperature distribution, stress contours, and predicted number of cycles to failure for defined hot-spots.

B.3 Digital Twin & AI Software Simulation

· Objective: Develop and test the tri-tiered autonomy stack.
· Synthetic Data Generation: The ASPEN and CFD models will generate time-series data for:
  · Normal operation across varying inlet conditions.
  · Fault conditions (e.g., gradual clog simulated by rising pressure drop, sensor drift).
· AI Training & Testing:
  1. Tier 2 (Optimizer): Trained via Model-Based Reinforcement Learning (MBRL) to maximize a reward function (high O2 yield, stable temperature, low power).
  2. Tier 3 (Sentinel): Trained as a classifier to recognize patterns (e.g., vibration FFT signatures, thermal response times) indicative of incipient pump failure or insulation degradation.
· Integration Test: The full stack will run a simulated 500-sol mission, including randomized fault injections, to measure system stability and AI response efficacy.

---

Appendix C: Literature Review & Foundational Assumptions

C.1 Annotated Foundational Research

Citation (Example) Key Finding Relevance to CHRSy-AI Design & Assumptions
Hecht et al. (2021) - MOXIE Demonstrated solid oxide electrolysis of CO2 on Mars; cell degradation observed. Justifies Catalyst-Free Approach: Highlights degradation as a critical risk for Mars ISRU. Our design assumes a thermal path avoids this failure mode.
Valluri et al. (2022) - Catalyst Review Details mechanisms of catalyst coking and poisoning in Sabatier systems. Quantifies the Problem: Provides data on performance decay rates, informing our assumption that catalyst mass replacement would be significant.
Jaworske & Colozza (2020) - NASA TM Surveys high-temperature material properties in planetary atmospheres. Informs Material Choice: Suggests Mo and W alloys as primary candidates for our reactor liner, forming the basis for our CFD material inputs.
Linne et al. (2017) - NASA TM Compares mass penalties of different ISRU architectures. Baselines Mass Savings: Provides the framework for our theoretical mass comparison in Table 1 of the main paper.

C.2 Documented Critical Assumptions

1. Hydrogen Parity Calculation: Assumes a 4-person crew consumes 2.4 kg of dry food per day with an average hydrogen mass fraction of 7%. Metabolic models are based on NASA Baseline Values and Assumptions Document (BVAD) data.
2. Martian Atmosphere Intake: Assumes a continuous, filterable supply of atmospheric CO2 at an average pressure of 6 mbar and composition of 95% CO2, ignoring the impact of global dust storms on intake availability for this first-order analysis.
3. AI Reliability: Assumes that an XAI model trained on high-fidelity synthetic data and validated within a Digital Twin will exhibit sufficient robustness to be considered for a flight system, pending later hardware-in-the-loop testing.

